<raw><![CDATA[    Investing.com - The euro slid to a two-and-a-half month low against the pound on Thursday, as sentiment on the single currency was hit by fresh concerns over the region’s debt crisis and worries over the outlook for economic growth.EUR/GBP hit 0.8250 during European morning trade, the pair’s lowest since January 16; the pair subsequently consolidated at 0.8255, slipping 0.18%.The pair was likely to find support at 0.8221, the low of January 9 and a 16-month low and resistance at 0.8324, Wednesday’s high.Concerns over Spain’s fiscal health mounted on Wednesday, as the cost of insuring the country’s debt against default climbed following a poorly received government bond auction.Meanwhile, European Central Bank President Mario Draghi warned that "downside risks to the economic outlook prevail" after the central bank kept its benchmark interest rate unchanged at a record low of 1%.In the U.K. earlier, unexpectedly weak data on factory output cast doubts over the strength of the country’s economic recovery.The Office for National Statistics said that manufacturing production in the U.K. fell by 1.0% in February and the previous month’s figures was revised down to show a drop of 0.3%, giving an annual decline of 1.4%.Industrial production rose 0.4% in February, slightly above expectations for a 0.3% gain.Meanwhile, investors were looking ahead to the Bank of England’s rate decision later in the session.The euro was lower against the U.S. dollar and the yen, with EUR/USD shedding 0.33% to hit 1.3097 and EUR/JPY dropping 0.70% to hit 107.60.Later Thursday, Germany was to publish official data on industrial production, while the U.S. was to publish government data on unemployment claims.             ]]></raw>
